  "report": {
    "sections": {
      "What we found": "The estimate that stands out most is the model's projection of your chance of survival over the next 12 months, which it puts at about 74%. In plain terms, this model reads your overall picture as carrying a meaningfully higher-than-usual risk of not surviving the year. This particular model is considered reliable, though its confidence in this individual estimate is moderate \u2014 so it deserves attention, but it is an estimate, not a certainty or a diagnosis. A second reliable model also sees a roughly even chance that this hospital stay could be longer than typical. Looking at your recorded labs myself, several liver-related values are elevated together \u2014 AST (168) and ALT (96) are both above the usual range, with total bilirubin mildly high (1.7) and platelets on the low side (95) \u2014 a pattern worth reviewing as a group. Your recorded blood pressure also runs low (systolic around 85\u201389, mean arterial pressure around 62) while your heart rate runs somewhat fast (mid-90s to 105). Sodium is low (130), potassium slightly high (5.2), and blood urea nitrogen elevated (35).",
      "What may be contributing": "The mortality estimate leans most on your kidney- and salt-related numbers \u2014 creatinine, blood urea nitrogen, and sodium. Your BUN is raised and your sodium is low, which the model weighs heavily, though your creatinine itself is actually low. The prolonged-stay estimate draws on your BUN alongside your liver-related labs (AST and bilirubin), and indeed those liver values cluster together in a way a clinician would want to look at as one picture rather than in isolation. Separately, your low blood pressure paired with a faster heart rate is another linked pattern in the recorded data. These are associations the model has picked up on, not proven causes \u2014 they point to areas to explore, not conclusions.",
      "What this means": "The most heavily-weighted findings come from reliable models, which is why they carry weight, but even reliable tools give estimates rather than facts, and here the confidence behind the mortality figure is only moderate \u2014 so treat the exact number as a signal to look closer, not a verdict. A separate estimate about being readmitted within 30 days comes from a model flagged as weak and with lower confidence, so I'd give it little weight. A likelihood of underlying respiratory disease (around 64%) comes from a reliable model but with lower confidence, so it too should be held loosely. None of this confirms any condition; it describes patterns in your data that merit a careful clinical conversation.",
      "What to do next": "Share these results with your care team and ask them to review the elevated liver enzymes and bilirubin together, along with your low sodium, raised BUN, low platelets, and the low blood pressure with faster heart rate. Ask which findings they feel are most important and whether any warrant closer monitoring or follow-up testing. Because several estimates carry lower confidence, it's fair to ask your clinician how much weight they'd personally place on each.",
      "When to seek care urgently": "Seek urgent medical attention if you experience chest pain, severe shortness of breath, fainting or near-fainting, confusion, a very fast or irregular heartbeat, yellowing of the skin or eyes, unusual bleeding or bruising, or any sudden severe symptom that feels alarming."
    },
    "disclaimer": "This summary is generated by a computer model to help you understand your health information. It is not a diagnosis and not a substitute for advice from a qualified clinician. Always talk to your healthcare provider about your results and any decisions."
